  "prompt": "What is the difference between dedicated graphics and shared graphics?",
  "response": "Here's a comparison between dedicated and shared graphics:\n\nDedicated Graphics:\n1. Separate graphics processing unit (GPU)\n2. Has its own dedicated video memory (VRAM)\n3. Higher performance for graphics-intensive tasks\n4. Better for gaming, video editing, 3D rendering\n5. Consumes more power\n6. More expensive\n7. Generates more heat\n8. Usually found in high-end laptops and desktops\n\nShared Graphics:\n1. Integrated into the main processor (CPU)\n2. Uses system RAM instead of dedicated VRAM\n3. Lower performance for graphics tasks\n4. Suitable for basic computing, web browsing, light applications\n5. Lower power consumption\n6. More cost-effective\n7. Generates less heat\n8. Commonly found in budget laptops and compact devices\n\nThe main difference is that dedicated graphics have a separate, more powerful GPU with its own memory, while shared graphics use the CPU's integrated graphics capabilities and system memory, resulting in lower performance but better energy efficiency and lower cost.",
